WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.600
I'm a staff engineer, staff software engineer at GitHub and

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:07.000
promise I know how to use computers.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:11.200
I'm an app proto enthusiast, why I'm here

00:00:11.200 --> 00:00:16.660
, and also a member of the chronically online and really

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:19.860
, really love online communities.

00:00:19.860 --> 00:00:23.160
I work remote and so online communities is really how I engage

00:00:23.160 --> 00:00:25.190
with a lot of folks and so that's what I got

00:00:25.330 --> 00:00:26.550
really interested in.

00:00:26.940 --> 00:00:28.880
I co-host the Overcommitted podcast.

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:31.000
I'm going to be recording this weekend.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:32.900
If you want to talk about your experience here, let me

00:00:32.900 --> 00:00:34.460
know because we're going to do a special episode.

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:37.920
And I also brought some stickers that I'll put out once

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:41.350
I find where all of the stickers are congregating.

00:00:41.350 --> 00:00:44.910
So a few months ago, I had this thought that I

00:00:44.910 --> 00:00:47.640
thought was a brilliant idea.

00:00:47.640 --> 00:00:49.830
I was like, why isn't there a Goodreads

00:00:49.830 --> 00:00:51.620
or like a letterbox on at proto?

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:53.180
This does not exist yet.

00:00:53.230 --> 00:00:56.280
And so I started building this app called Collective which was

00:00:56.500 --> 00:00:58.220
sort of, you know, the same thing.

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:01.130
Turns out it did exist.

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:03.460
And there's quite a few of them.

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:07.110
One of them in particular that I really like is called pop

00:01:07.110 --> 00:01:07.630
feed.

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:08.300
social.

00:01:08.300 --> 00:01:11.320
They did this way, way better than I had done.

00:01:11.420 --> 00:01:13.990
And I highly recommend you check it out if you're interested

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:14.860
in something like that.

00:01:15.090 --> 00:01:21.690
But one thing that I got really stumped by while working

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:25.690
on this problem was I have an online developer community for Over

00:01:25.690 --> 00:01:26.390
committed.

00:01:26.410 --> 00:01:27.740
And we have a book club.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:30.360
So we like to read technical books together.

00:01:30.400 --> 00:01:33.140
If you are also interested in reading books, let me know

00:01:33.140 --> 00:01:33.300
.

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:34.540
You're welcome to join.

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:37.250
Right now we coordinate on Discord.

00:01:37.250 --> 00:01:40.990
And Discord is great, but I really wanted Collective to

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:44.210
help, you know, facilitate the book club situation.

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:46.130
Because it's really awkward to say, all right, we

00:01:46.130 --> 00:01:48.010
're going to put our list on GitHub and then we're

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:50.980
going to have the conversations in Discord and then we'll have

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:51.730
some events.

00:01:51.730 --> 00:01:53.450
And it's just, it's kind of a mess.

00:01:53.500 --> 00:01:54.940
So I was like, you know what, wouldn't it

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:56.280
be nice if we could solve this problem?

00:01:56.510 --> 00:02:00.360
Discord now owns our member list.

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:02.090
It owns our reading history.

00:02:02.090 --> 00:02:05.780
It owns every single conversation we've had about every single book

00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:05.980
.

00:02:05.980 --> 00:02:09.220
If Discord decides to change their terms, which I'm sure

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:14.180
they would never do, then we lose all of that.

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:18.180
The entire history of our entire community can just be erased.

00:02:18.230 --> 00:02:20.700
And that's a real bummer.

00:02:20.700 --> 00:02:23.910
It's not necessarily just a Discord problem.

00:02:23.910 --> 00:02:25.820
This is also a platform problem.

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:30.370
Every single group that has been built online on Reddit or on

00:02:30.370 --> 00:02:35.090
Facebook or on Slack, the platform owns every one of those

00:02:35.090 --> 00:02:37.480
spaces and the platform gets to make all of the decisions about

00:02:37.670 --> 00:02:38.460
what happens there.

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:45.680
And when the platform disappears, that means the community disappears too

00:02:45.950 --> 00:02:46.060
.

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:49.580
You've got Google Plus, MySpace, Twitter, what

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:52.140
once existed of it, all gone.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:56.490
Along with every single conversation and every shared memory and piece of

00:02:56.490 --> 00:02:57.500
community knowledge.

00:03:01.260 --> 00:03:03.480
So I think that AppRoto did a really great job

00:03:03.480 --> 00:03:04.860
of solving personal ownership.

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:07.210
Your posts live in your repo.

00:03:07.210 --> 00:03:10.050
Your social graph is completely under your control.

00:03:10.050 --> 00:03:12.970
And your identity is portable to wherever you want to bring it

00:03:12.970 --> 00:03:13.140
.

00:03:13.140 --> 00:03:15.080
But there's still an open question one.

00:03:15.190 --> 00:03:19.180
Question about what about shared things?

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:21.040
So what about book clubs?

00:03:21.040 --> 00:03:23.020
Or community projects?

00:03:23.020 --> 00:03:24.700
Or the group chat itself?

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:27.780
Does that belong to the individual or does it belong to the

00:03:28.010 --> 00:03:28.840
group as a whole?

00:03:28.950 --> 00:03:34.560
So these are the design questions that I was thinking about going

00:03:34.560 --> 00:03:35.110
into this.

00:03:35.110 --> 00:03:37.660
Because I wanted to build something that would make it so that

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:41.030
my group could live not just in collective itself, not just

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:43.540
on blue sky where we chat to each other.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:45.980
I want it to exist on its own and not be controlled

00:03:45.980 --> 00:03:47.980
by whichever platform we are working in.

00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:51.900
So the first question was where does the data live?

00:03:51.900 --> 00:03:53.550
Is this a shared PDS?

00:03:53.550 --> 00:03:56.000
Is it someone's personal repo?

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:58.140
Whoever created the group?

00:03:58.430 --> 00:03:59.170
We'll get into that.

00:03:59.170 --> 00:04:00.220
That can be problematic.

00:04:01.010 --> 00:04:04.860
Yep.

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:06.540
Somebody is familiar with this problem.

00:04:06.540 --> 00:04:09.240
And then who controls it?

00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:12.830
Like does the person who created the group get automatic full control

00:04:12.830 --> 00:04:14.180
over that group forever?

00:04:15.260 --> 00:04:15.570
No.

00:04:15.570 --> 00:04:16.590
Absolutely not.

00:04:16.590 --> 00:04:17.720
Like that's crazy.

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:19.930
Because then, you know, anyway, we'll get into

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:20.300
that.

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:24.140
And then how do members themselves relate to the group?

00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:27.670
Do they have to sign up through whatever group mechanism they're

00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:28.030
in?

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:32.220
What determines how a group, how an individual controls their own

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:33.980
affiliation with the group?

00:04:33.980 --> 00:04:37.260
And so those are the things that I brought into thinking on

00:04:37.260 --> 00:04:37.820
this problem.

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:39.920
And I do want to give some shout outs to a ton

00:04:40.010 --> 00:04:43.790
of folks in the community that have already been thinking a lot

00:04:43.790 --> 00:04:44.640
about this.

00:04:44.640 --> 00:04:48.530
And that their work has gone into what I ended up building

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:48.860
.

00:04:48.860 --> 00:04:52.060
So Brian Newbold, I just met you this morning.

00:04:52.060 --> 00:04:54.060
Sorry, I'm stalking you online.

00:04:54.060 --> 00:04:59.370
But he had some great, great leaflets on this.

00:04:59.370 --> 00:05:00.530
Nick Jerakines.

00:05:00.530 --> 00:05:03.250
I don't think he's in here, but I technically

00:05:03.290 --> 00:05:06.200
work with him as how he's been introducing me today.

00:05:06.200 --> 00:05:08.780
We work at GitHub together and I've been bugging him

00:05:08.780 --> 00:05:09.020
.

00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:10.920
He's had some great stuff.

00:05:10.940 --> 00:05:13.310
I have Mary, the front page team.

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:15.980
Erland, who I don't believe is here.

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:18.510
And then also I wanted to give a shout out to Amelia

00:05:18.510 --> 00:05:22.820
who has been very patient at answering all of my questions here

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:23.160
.

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:24.700
Yes.

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:28.920
So I've been collecting these and I built a thing with

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:29.580
that.

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:34.300
So AppRoto's philosophy is really your data, your

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:34.700
repo.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:38.870
That works for personal data but not so great for shared state

00:05:38.870 --> 00:05:39.100
.

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:42.630
It doesn't really fit neatly into this one person's repo

00:05:42.630 --> 00:05:42.820
.

00:05:42.820 --> 00:05:46.450
So how do we extend that ownership model to collective data without

00:05:46.540 --> 00:05:49.020
losing what it is that makes AppRoto so special?

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:55.100
And this is the approach that I came up with which is

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:55.990
open social.

00:05:55.990 --> 00:05:56.680
community.

00:05:56.700 --> 00:06:00.240
It isn't really the answer, but it's an answer

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:00.510
.

00:06:00.510 --> 00:06:03.160
And, you know, you can try it out and see

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:05.200
if this is a thing that fits you or built your own

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:05.610
thing.

00:06:05.750 --> 00:06:07.420
That's the beauty of this community.

00:06:07.420 --> 00:06:10.820
It's group infrastructure.

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:12.490
It's not itself an app view.

00:06:12.510 --> 00:06:15.970
It's just an infrastructure and a set of APIs that anybody

00:06:15.980 --> 00:06:18.930
can integrate with, any app you can integrate with, or

00:06:18.930 --> 00:06:21.420
any community can manage their own group through.

00:06:21.420 --> 00:06:24.730
And I'm going to walk through a couple of the design

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:26.660
decisions that were made.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:30.410
So the first one, which is the most important to that

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:35.260
ownership question, is groups are stored as AppRoto identities

00:06:35.260 --> 00:06:36.060
themselves.

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:37.330
They're their own did.

00:06:37.390 --> 00:06:40.620
I've separated the group infrastructure from the app because I don

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:43.030
't want to get into the situation where I've built this

00:06:43.030 --> 00:06:45.660
fantastic community and then the app goes in a direction that I

00:06:45.660 --> 00:06:47.860
don't agree with and then we're just completely locked in

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:48.040
.

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:51.280
Membership is a two-way handshake.

00:06:51.280 --> 00:06:53.030
Not anybody can just join any group.

00:06:53.030 --> 00:06:55.450
I mean, maybe there are some groups who are okay with

00:06:55.450 --> 00:06:57.480
that, but there's definitely some that aren't.

00:06:57.480 --> 00:06:59.100
And you can't just say, hey, I'm going

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:00.400
to join this group now.

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:03.500
And then, finally, there's a wrapper pattern to have

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:07.840
shared content that makes it easy to show within an app view

00:07:07.970 --> 00:07:14.300
without necessarily overloading that repo with a lot of extra stuff

00:07:14.300 --> 00:07:14.300
.

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:16.680
So what does that look like?

00:07:16.680 --> 00:07:19.180
Every group gets its own did.

00:07:19.180 --> 00:07:22.820
So, for example, my book club is its own web

00:07:22.820 --> 00:07:25.060
, did web over committed.

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:25.560
dev.

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:28.790
It has its own handle, its own repo on a PD

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:33.100
S and then group shared data is stored within that repo.

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:36.960
That makes a group a first-class citizen of the protocol

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:39.100
itself and it means that it gets to take advantage of a

00:07:39.100 --> 00:07:40.430
lot of the stuff that's already built there.

00:07:40.620 --> 00:07:43.180
It's not a row in some apps database.

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:46.170
It's an entity with its own identity.

00:07:46.170 --> 00:07:49.370
And just like personal dids, that entity is, at

00:07:49.370 --> 00:07:51.560
least, hopefully, portable.

00:07:55.340 --> 00:08:00.130
And then the infrastructure, instead of being an app view itself

00:08:00.220 --> 00:08:02.280
, this is what the infrastructure looks like.

00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:05.420
So I can have collective, which is, has access to

00:08:05.520 --> 00:08:07.340
open social community.

00:08:07.340 --> 00:08:11.060
But then you can also have your own other apps that have

00:08:11.250 --> 00:08:12.040
access to it.

00:08:12.150 --> 00:08:15.340
Any app view can connect to it.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:18.340
And you can also have, you know, your podcast app

00:08:18.340 --> 00:08:22.060
or your reading app or multiple of those if you want.

00:08:22.060 --> 00:08:24.270
Maybe you want to multiple, you want to support blue sky

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:26.450
and black sky and Erosky, all from the same

00:08:26.460 --> 00:08:28.980
thing, to have one group, then that's totally reasonable

00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:29.180
.

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:33.500
Each app gets its own namespace within open social.

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:35.380
So collective stores app.

00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:36.760
collectivesocial.

00:08:36.870 --> 00:08:37.350
group.

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:38.530
list lexicons.

00:08:38.530 --> 00:08:43.490
And then other apps cannot create other lexicons within the

00:08:43.490 --> 00:08:47.980
group unless they have access to those namespaces.

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:51.520
That prevents other apps from overriding data that, you

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:54.370
know, you don't want somebody else to be able to

00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:57.710
change the data for your podcast app from collective or vice versa

00:08:57.710 --> 00:08:57.710
.

00:08:57.950 --> 00:09:00.700
Same group, different data and no conflicts.

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:03.720
The group there is the shared context then.

00:09:03.830 --> 00:09:07.890
And then the group gets a decision on which apps it also

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:08.610
has access to.

00:09:08.610 --> 00:09:10.520
So if an app does go in a direction that the group

00:09:10.740 --> 00:09:13.040
decides that they don't want access to, they can also

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:16.040
prevent that group from having access or that app from having access

00:09:16.150 --> 00:09:16.700
to that group.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:21.020
The next one.

00:09:21.020 --> 00:09:22.860
So membership as a two-way handshake.

00:09:22.860 --> 00:09:26.160
This means that there is a membership record in an individual's

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:28.400
repo and then also in the group repo.

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:32.080
That confirms that not only has the member agreed that they want

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:34.330
to be involved in this group, but the group has agreed

00:09:34.330 --> 00:09:38.680
that that person is involved in that membership record.

00:09:38.910 --> 00:09:44.500
That means that an individual can leave any time without needing permission

00:09:44.500 --> 00:09:46.440
from the group to leave the group.

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:49.060
And then at the same time, the group can, you

00:09:49.110 --> 00:09:52.160
know, excommunicate somebody if needed without having to get

00:09:52.190 --> 00:09:54.460
permission to update that individual's repo.

00:09:57.420 --> 00:10:00.040
And that's a nice opportunity for privacy here, too.

00:10:00.150 --> 00:10:03.010
So you can have a group of membership records that, you

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:05.480
know, have hashes that are storing instead of the actual

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:09.190
membership identity, which means that then you don't necessarily have

00:10:09.190 --> 00:10:11.240
a list of all the people that are in the group sitting

00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:13.020
in the repo, which can also be beneficial.

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:16.900
And then the wrapper pattern.

00:10:16.930 --> 00:10:20.130
So in this case, this is for user content.

00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:23.820
So the group creates a wrapper around that content.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:27.340
Bob, in this case, will own the book review.

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:29.740
They create the book review and they own that content.

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:33.460
But then the group owns a wrap or wrapper around that content

00:10:33.460 --> 00:10:33.620
.

00:10:33.620 --> 00:10:36.510
That means that the group has access to remove that content from

00:10:36.510 --> 00:10:37.980
the group if needed.

00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:40.220
And then Bob, if he decides to leave the group,

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:42.770
he still owns his own book review, which is nice.

00:10:45.900 --> 00:10:48.780
Then the group repo also ends up being an index of references

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:52.390
and not necessarily a copy of all of the content, which

00:10:52.390 --> 00:10:54.380
can also be a bit problematic.

00:10:54.380 --> 00:10:58.400
And then this is what it looks like end-to-

00:10:58.670 --> 00:10:59.150
end.

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:04.420
So you register an app, in this case collective, as

00:11:04.420 --> 00:11:05.970
an app view with OpenSocial.

00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:08.850
Community and get an API key which can be used for

00:11:09.470 --> 00:11:10.190
authentication.

00:11:10.190 --> 00:11:14.540
And then you can create your group through those collective APIs.

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:17.540
I'm still working on some PDS things involved to make

00:11:17.540 --> 00:11:20.630
that simpler because nobody wants to have to create a did and

00:11:20.630 --> 00:11:22.230
then put it over anywhere else.

00:11:22.230 --> 00:11:23.420
But we'll get to that.

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:26.320
Members join through that two-way handshake, which,

00:11:26.320 --> 00:11:28.110
again, can be within the app view if you'd like

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:29.400
or through OpenSocial.

00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:29.980
Community.

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:32.140
It has its own UI for that.

00:11:32.210 --> 00:11:36.940
And then members contribute content via their wrappers, also through

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:37.500
APIs.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:42.450
They support community creation, membership management, namespace, record

00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:43.260
storage.

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:47.330
Because I work in the enterprise space at GitHub, there's

00:11:47.330 --> 00:11:51.230
also audit logging and custom roles and permissions, which were probably

00:11:51.230 --> 00:11:52.970
a little bit unnecessary.

00:11:53.110 --> 00:11:55.020
But it's what I know.

00:11:55.020 --> 00:11:59.690
And because I don't want to just talk about it,

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:02.250
I'm going to show you a little demo through images.

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:05.000
So this is what it actually looks like on the web.

00:12:05.220 --> 00:12:06.940
Both OpenSocial and Collective are up.

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:08.460
Like I said, don't use Collective.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:09.980
It's not very good.

00:12:09.980 --> 00:12:11.260
But OpenSocial is up.

00:12:11.260 --> 00:12:13.180
And I've spent a lot more time looking at this.

00:12:13.180 --> 00:12:15.540
So this is how you can register a developer app.

00:12:15.540 --> 00:12:17.650
You can go in and initially set, like, what are

00:12:17.740 --> 00:12:20.160
the lexicons that you want groups to be able to

00:12:20.590 --> 00:12:20.780
manage.

00:12:20.840 --> 00:12:23.730
And you can say, with the regular create, read,

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:26.670
update, or delete, do you want everybody in the group

00:12:26.680 --> 00:12:29.420
to be able to do that or just group members?

00:12:29.420 --> 00:12:31.780
So you can have a completely open one or say, like

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:34.140
, eh, let's say that only admins can delete

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:35.180
things or something.

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:38.580
Next, you can view the group itself.

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:40.520
The list of members.

00:12:40.620 --> 00:12:43.100
You can search through it.

00:12:43.100 --> 00:12:45.820
See who has registered with this group.

00:12:46.850 --> 00:12:51.100
And also have different community settings.

00:12:51.100 --> 00:12:55.170
So community admin can configure settings like whether the community is completely

00:12:55.230 --> 00:12:55.520
open.

00:12:55.520 --> 00:12:56.360
Anybody can join.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:59.930
Whether they want it to be closed where they need approval.

00:12:59.950 --> 00:13:03.580
Or whether it's private but asterisk on private.

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:06.430
Because everything's in a repo in app proto.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:09.650
So private doesn't really exist just yet.

00:13:09.680 --> 00:13:10.860
But it will.

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:12.540
There's some very smart people working on that problem.

00:13:12.540 --> 00:13:17.820
These governance decisions are explicit and visible.

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:18.660
They're not buried.

00:13:18.660 --> 00:13:21.160
They're just all stored within the group's repo.

00:13:21.270 --> 00:13:26.140
And then finally, there's app permissions.

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:29.240
So a community admin can say, I want access to this

00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:31.970
app but not this one within this group context.

00:13:32.060 --> 00:13:35.700
And theoretically, there's also some opportunity here to create some

00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:39.780
sort of a record now saying this is where this group has

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:40.410
access to.

00:13:40.630 --> 00:13:44.060
Maybe we can just create, like, a Steam or Rob

00:13:44.060 --> 00:13:47.280
lox type app store where you can access all of these

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:48.240
different apps.

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:51.790
You can access collective or blue sky or black sky or stream

00:13:51.790 --> 00:13:52.170
place.

00:13:52.170 --> 00:13:53.120
All within one space.

00:13:53.120 --> 00:13:55.740
And you can say these are the places that my community is

00:13:55.740 --> 00:13:56.660
gathering.

00:13:56.700 --> 00:14:01.490
So that it's easy to gather across different contexts.

00:14:01.580 --> 00:14:04.620
And then finally, collective.

00:14:04.620 --> 00:14:08.060
So you have the ability to discover new communities.

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:09.910
Search for them and view them.

00:14:09.910 --> 00:14:12.220
Each community has its own handle.

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:13.100
Membership status.

00:14:13.100 --> 00:14:16.490
You can see here, we've got overcommitted.

00:14:16.490 --> 00:14:18.670
dev, which is the overcommitted book club, which

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:19.950
I already have access to.

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:22.620
And then a few of the book club features on collective.

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:25.920
Because why would I build just one app when I could build

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:26.220
two?

00:14:26.220 --> 00:14:29.820
Is what the overcommitted group actually looks like.

00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:32.430
So it has a collection of lists of different books, including

00:14:32.430 --> 00:14:33.900
the book that we're currently reading.

00:14:33.900 --> 00:14:38.220
And an ability to set different sections by date.

00:14:38.940 --> 00:14:41.550
An ability to comment on different sections of the book.

00:14:41.790 --> 00:14:45.180
And an ability to make sure that you're not spoiling

00:14:45.180 --> 00:14:50.220
those things so that you complete the book reading before you actually

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:51.260
participate in the discussion.

00:14:51.260 --> 00:14:54.760
This is the most recent book that we read, Writing for

00:14:54.870 --> 00:14:55.900
Developers.

00:14:55.900 --> 00:14:59.560
Cynthia Dunlap and Peter Sarna are both very active

00:14:59.740 --> 00:15:00.540
on Blue Sky.

00:15:00.540 --> 00:15:03.660
And I highly recommend you check out the book if you are

00:15:03.660 --> 00:15:06.990
in the very small niche of developers who also like to write

00:15:07.050 --> 00:15:07.880
for other people.

00:15:07.980 --> 00:15:13.620
And then, yeah, so the full app is available at

00:15:13.670 --> 00:15:14.370
opensocial.

00:15:14.390 --> 00:15:14.940
community.

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:19.060
If you're interested in building on it, let me know

00:15:19.130 --> 00:15:19.260
.

00:15:19.260 --> 00:15:22.020
Because I would love to see how this actually scales across other

00:15:22.020 --> 00:15:22.460
apps.

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:25.020
Like I said, there's a lot of features that are

00:15:25.020 --> 00:15:27.470
built in already that are probably overkill.

00:15:27.470 --> 00:15:30.640
But -- And then we also have collective social, which I

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:34.360
think is mostly just for book club organization.

00:15:34.360 --> 00:15:38.780
But we also have some movies and some other ways to collect

00:15:38.780 --> 00:15:40.970
podcasts and things like that.

00:15:40.970 --> 00:15:43.700
So yeah, that one is in alpha, I will say

00:15:43.770 --> 00:15:46.770
, as a way of saying it's not quite ready.

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:51.550
But what about -- so this brings me to some important points

00:15:51.790 --> 00:15:52.460
about groups.

00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:55.260
So specifically about governance and moderation.

00:15:55.260 --> 00:15:58.410
So one of the things that Brian brought up in one of

00:15:58.460 --> 00:16:01.840
his posts brought to my attention is from Nathan Schneider,

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:05.180
who coined the term implicit feudalism, which is a

00:16:05.180 --> 00:16:08.100
very large way of saying that there's a default pattern where

00:16:08.100 --> 00:16:11.920
whoever creates a thing online typically ends up owning that thing.

00:16:11.920 --> 00:16:13.800
And I think that that goes in multiple ways.

00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:16.380
That's not just the group itself.

00:16:16.380 --> 00:16:21.830
It's the platform that actually allows the creation of the group

00:16:22.110 --> 00:16:22.380
.

00:16:22.380 --> 00:16:28.900
So by default, there is a bias towards building communities as

00:16:28.900 --> 00:16:32.170
fiefdoms, where somebody owns that group.

00:16:32.170 --> 00:16:35.260
And they want to, of course, increase membership and be

00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:37.570
the person who owns that community.

00:16:37.570 --> 00:16:40.060
But that doesn't -- that means that that person has absolute

00:16:40.060 --> 00:16:41.080
power over the group.

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:44.510
And a member needs to start seeking permission to be able to

00:16:44.510 --> 00:16:47.180
do anything, which is something that I've experienced a lot

00:16:47.180 --> 00:16:48.190
in community spaces.

00:16:48.190 --> 00:16:50.190
It would be really nice if we did this thing, but

00:16:50.190 --> 00:16:52.830
then they need to get permission from the person who runs the

00:16:52.830 --> 00:16:56.380
community to actually do that instead of just doing the thing.

00:16:56.380 --> 00:17:00.770
So what shared groups on AppProto can enable for us

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:03.590
is we can have different governance patterns.

00:17:03.660 --> 00:17:06.600
What does that actually look like when we have control over it

00:17:06.600 --> 00:17:08.220
separate from the platform?

00:17:09.340 --> 00:17:12.750
We have an ability to make that completely transparent where the rules

00:17:12.750 --> 00:17:16.280
are visible for everybody and that you can create rules that fit

00:17:16.500 --> 00:17:19.000
your community because it's not a one-size-fits

00:17:19.090 --> 00:17:20.030
-all approach here.

00:17:20.030 --> 00:17:24.220
Different communities are going to want different ways of managing themselves.

00:17:24.220 --> 00:17:26.200
And so we want to be able to make sure that it

00:17:26.310 --> 00:17:29.240
's flexible enough that they can do what they want to do

00:17:29.240 --> 00:17:30.380
across all of the different apps.

00:17:30.380 --> 00:17:35.440
And then moderation is the other spot that I've been looking

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:39.630
at this from, which is a layered moderation approach that is

00:17:39.630 --> 00:17:41.180
already built in.

00:17:41.180 --> 00:17:43.580
This is a thing that already exists with labelers.

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:46.050
And the group itself can act as its own labeler.

00:17:46.050 --> 00:17:50.360
Admins can approve labelers that align with the community values

00:17:50.580 --> 00:17:54.540
and then we can layer on that by moderating within the

00:17:54.540 --> 00:17:55.660
specific spaces that they're in.

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:59.890
And then individual members can still add their own labelers or

00:17:59.980 --> 00:18:02.340
muting or anything like that on top of that so that

00:18:02.340 --> 00:18:05.410
they see exactly the stuff that they want to see and nothing

00:18:05.410 --> 00:18:05.660
else.

00:18:05.660 --> 00:18:11.420
The advantage here for using this wrapper pattern means that there's

00:18:11.420 --> 00:18:14.460
an implicit moderation built into the group itself.

00:18:14.460 --> 00:18:18.060
You can remove a wrapper and that content is hidden from the

00:18:18.060 --> 00:18:18.760
community.

00:18:18.760 --> 00:18:20.380
But the user's data is still intact.

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:25.000
You can remove a membership proof and that revokes access without

00:18:25.110 --> 00:18:29.500
actually destroying the rest of the access to the group.

00:18:29.750 --> 00:18:35.100
You can delete content which leaves a tombstone preserving conversation structure

00:18:35.100 --> 00:18:35.100
.

00:18:35.100 --> 00:18:39.220
And then there's options there for, you know, appealing

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:40.450
those moderation decisions.

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:42.840
You can, you know, maybe just soft delete those things

00:18:42.840 --> 00:18:45.020
and then bring them back so that they can be appealed

00:18:45.120 --> 00:18:45.460
easily.

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:49.100
There's still a lot to figure out.

00:18:49.100 --> 00:18:51.500
I think that private groups is probably the thing that I'm

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:53.180
most interested in.

00:18:53.180 --> 00:18:56.610
It's important not just, you know, because not every

00:18:56.610 --> 00:18:58.460
group needs to be available.

00:18:58.460 --> 00:18:59.980
What if it's just your friend's group chat?

00:18:59.980 --> 00:19:02.410
You know, that doesn't necessarily need to have everything visible

00:19:02.410 --> 00:19:04.860
online, but it's also important for community safety.

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:08.540
I participate in a lot of parenting groups online because I am

00:19:08.540 --> 00:19:11.740
a mom of three young kids and none of us want pictures

00:19:11.740 --> 00:19:13.680
of our kids shared on the internet.

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:16.380
So having that privacy is extremely important.

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:17.660
Group creation.

00:19:17.660 --> 00:19:21.500
I've been talking to Bailey a little bit about that today

00:19:21.500 --> 00:19:25.050
, where there are some really awesome ideas on how to make

00:19:25.270 --> 00:19:28.460
this easy because you don't want to necessarily tell somebody,

00:19:28.460 --> 00:19:31.020
all right, if you want to have your own community,

00:19:31.020 --> 00:19:32.580
first set up a PDS.

00:19:32.650 --> 00:19:35.840
Like, that's not the way to sell anything to anybody

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:36.140
.

00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:39.860
So making that easy and frictionless when a user's using

00:19:39.910 --> 00:19:41.260
it is very critical.

00:19:41.980 --> 00:19:43.950
And then finally, how do we make this interoperable

00:19:44.140 --> 00:19:44.140
?

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:46.890
Not just with app proto, but what about the activity pub

00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:47.050
?

00:19:47.050 --> 00:19:50.380
Like, why would the decentralized communities need to be separated?

00:19:50.380 --> 00:19:52.940
We can bring them together within their own identity.

00:19:53.010 --> 00:19:57.740
So why are groups important?

00:19:57.740 --> 00:20:00.040
What becomes possible?

00:20:00.090 --> 00:20:04.300
So then this means that the whole reason why this is important

00:20:04.300 --> 00:20:09.100
is the playlist that somebody creates on Spotify that's owned by

00:20:09.260 --> 00:20:13.420
the friend group that's not necessarily owned by Spotify itself.

00:20:13.420 --> 00:20:16.990
A study group can have their own shared notes belonging to students

00:20:17.070 --> 00:20:17.180
.

00:20:17.180 --> 00:20:23.660
Discussion forums can stay with the author and not with the

00:20:23.730 --> 00:20:26.760
individual or not with the group, the platform.

00:20:26.860 --> 00:20:31.530
I think that decentralization is not just about personal data sovereignty

00:20:31.580 --> 00:20:33.660
, but it's also about collective data sovereignty.

00:20:33.660 --> 00:20:37.740
A community's shared knowledge and history and spaces should belong to

00:20:37.740 --> 00:20:41.880
the community forever, not just while they're on the platform

00:20:41.990 --> 00:20:42.540
that they're on.

00:20:42.640 --> 00:20:46.780
So the question, the answer to who owns the group chat

00:20:46.780 --> 00:20:48.540
, the group should.

00:20:48.540 --> 00:20:51.700
I'd love to talk more about this if this is a

00:20:51.700 --> 00:20:54.520
thing that you're interested in.

00:20:54.540 --> 00:20:56.300
I've got some resources linked here.

00:20:56.300 --> 00:20:58.810
You're welcome to check out and I've also got some

00:20:58.810 --> 00:21:00.860
links to all of these community references.

